<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-683-865  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 683 865.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  Dec 1990 v13 n12 p47(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The art of medicine. (the impact of computer in the production ofmedical art; includes related article on Colorado StateUniversity's Vesalius Project that is developing a 3D anatomy database)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mahoney, Diana Phillips.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer graphics technologies provide medical artists with newtools to ease the process and improve the output of medicalillustration.andP;  Medical artists must combine creativity, anunderstanding of visual graphics effects and knowledge of anatomyand physiology.andP;  The computer enables artists to save drawingtime; helps produce and enhance images in unique, useful andcreative ways; simplifies the drawing revision; and eliminatesdrawing preparation, drying and cleanup time.andP;  Critics say thecomputer imposes boundaries that limit creativity and can notcapture fine detail.andP;  Numerous computer-based medical artpresentations at the Association of Medical Illustrators meetingand the many computer-related classes in Johns HopkinsUniversity's graduate medical illustration program illustrates thetrend to computerized medical art.andP;  Several products andapplications are briefly discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MedicineComputer-Aided Design and DraftingGraphics SoftwareUtilizationProductsGraphic ArtsApplicationsSoftware Packages.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>